                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d289">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/4310: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-11-08T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 8, 1934—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>164. Your 310, November 7, 3 p.m. The Argentine Ambassador called this morning to
                    inform the Department, by instruction of Saavedra Lamas, that the latter had
                    instructed the Argentine Ministers in La Paz and Asunción a few days ago to
                    sound out the Bolivian and Paraguayan Governments in order to ascertain whether
                    they would be favorable to renewed peace proposals. In each case, the reply was
                    stated to have been favorable. Saavedra Lamas stated that what he had in mind
                    was a renewal of the mediation negotiations along the lines previously agreed
                    upon in the event that the League efforts proved unsuccessful.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
